begun to find your way through.

00:03:37.669 --> 00:03:38.860
It's available at Labyrinth.
 

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:44.370
Clarke is something of a
curmudgeon, and he offers

00:03:44.370 --> 00:03:49.878
interpretations,
which should provoke argument.

00:03:49.878 --> 00:03:55.474
For example,
he interprets the demography of

00:03:55.474 --> 00:04:00.158
England in the Malthusian
period,

00:04:00.158 --> 00:04:02.449
before the great surge in the
economy,

00:04:02.449 --> 00:04:09.007
in essentially Darwinian terms,
Darwinian both with respect to

00:04:09.007 --> 00:04:12.234
culture,
so social Darwinism,

00:04:12.234 --> 00:04:15.710
but also with respect to
biology.

00:04:15.710 --> 00:04:22.293
He flirts with the idea that
the children of the wealthy were

00:04:22.293 --> 00:04:28.550
genetically superior to other
children being born in early

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:34.805
modern England and that that
fact has something to do with

00:04:34.805 --> 00:04:41.720
why the great economic surge
took place first in England;

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:44.959
actually more broadly the
United Kingdom.

00:04:44.959 --> 00:04:50.036
